Here are two quick git tricks that I&rsquo;ve added to my toolbox lately&hellip;
I wanted to create a git alias that takes in argv from the command, but in the middle of the command. Here&rsquo;s the hack that I came up with for the [alias] section of my ~/.gitconfig:
[alias] # cherryfetch fetches a repo ($1) / branch ($2) and applies it rebased! # the &amp;&amp; true at the end eats up the appended args cherryfetch = !

I just patched puppet-gluster and puppet-ipa to bring their infrastructure up to date with the current state of affairs&hellip;
What&rsquo;s new?
Better README's Rake syntax checking (fewer oopsies) CI (testing) with travis on git push (automatic testing for everyone) Use of .pmtignore to ignore files from puppet module packages (finally) Pushing modules to the forge with blacksmith (sweet!) This last point deserves another mention. Puppetlabs created the "forge" to try to provide some sort of added value to their stewardship.

If you&rsquo;re a reader of my code or of this blog, it&rsquo;s no secret that I hack on a lot of puppet and vagrant. Recently I&rsquo;ve fooled around with a bit of docker, too. I realized that the vagrant, environments I built for puppet-gluster and puppet-ipa needed to be generalized, and they needed new features too. Therefore&hellip;
Introducing: Oh My Vagrant!
Oh My Vagrant is an attempt to provide an easy to use development environment so that you can be up and hacking quickly, and focusing on the real devops problems.

